Sepulchur Pasture

South of Midgaard's gates lies the field where the city's promises
to its dead are tested. Long before it bore this name, the land was
called the Ninth Acre -- beyond the ninth milestone, where
shepherd-priests rang a single bell at dusk to guide the lost. That
bell was a promise that someone was still listening.

As the city grew, caravan ambushes, dungeon attrition, and frontier
skirmishes produced more bodies than the Temple's crypts could absorb.
The city solved this the way it solves everything: with process. Road
dead were routed to the acre. Names were copied from signet rings or
witness testimony. Effects were cataloged. Graves were marked by
category if not by certainty. The old field became Sepulchur
Pasture, where mercy became a civic machine.

During the Ash-and-Iron Decades, a burial tariff called the
Tithe of Last Burdens was imposed to fund guards, carts, salt,
and bells. Families who could pay bought sanctified plots. Those who
could not were entered as "deferred names" and interred in common
furrows pending claim. Over time, a quiet industry formed around
grief: clerks charging for corrections, carriers misplacing evidence,
wardens delaying remains, brokers trading inheritance rumor.

When the Violet Compact's containment doctrine spread beyond the
inner reliquary corridors, the pasture became an outer quarantine
site. Certain remains -- plague-touched, curse-ridden, or arcane-
active -- were forbidden immediate burial. Holding pens, wardwire
trenches, and witness lantern circles were added. The Compact called
it public safety. Temple mourners called it trapping souls in legal
limbo. Both were right.

Then came the omen. After three mass interments, night watch heard
the gravebell ring twice for every pull: once from the tower, once
from somewhere beneath the furrows. Ledger irregularities followed --
names recorded without bodies, bodies interred without names, claim
tokens duplicated across unrelated dead. The phrase "deferred name"
stopped meaning paperwork and started meaning unrest.

Children in nearby wards still repeat at dusk:
"Pay the living, name the dead, and do not let the bell count
twice."

If the bell counts twice, it means the ledger has failed, and the
dead are doing their own accounting.

