the Attestation of Final Passage: a sworn document naming the
dead, the cause, the witness, and the disposition of remains.

This is why Sepulchur Pasture horrifies us.

Midgaard solved its burial crisis with process -- then let the
process rot. Road dead routed to a field. Names copied from signet
rings or witness testimony -- sometimes guessed. Graves marked by
category, not certainty. The shepherd-priests' bell became a
civic machine, and machines do not grieve. They process.

The "deferred names" appall us most. The dead entered into common
furrows pending claim, their rites withheld because no one paid
the Tithe of Last Burdens. In Mafdet, a guardian-name persists
beyond death. You cannot defer a name. You cannot suspend an identity
pending payment. A deferred name is a broken oath to someone who
can no longer protest.

The quiet industry around grief -- clerks charging for corrections,
carriers misplacing evidence, wardens delaying remains, brokers
trading inheritance rumor -- is predatory attestation at its most
obscene. In Mafdet, a Hazard Scribe who falsified a death attestation
would face the Shrine's justice -- swift and unsentimental.

The Violet Compact's quarantine doctrine turning the pasture into
a holding zone is familiar to our Quarantine Ledger. We classify
hazardous remains by tier. But we do not trap souls in legal
limbo. Quarantine is containment with a timeline. Indefinite holding
without review is abandonment wearing process as a mask.

The gravebell ringing twice -- once from the tower, once from
beneath the furrows -- is what happens when the ledger fails the
dead. Names without bodies. Bodies without names. In Mafdet, the
Dual-Attestation Protocol requires two independent verifications.
One record cannot contradict another without triggering review.

Midgaard's children whisper: "Pay the living, name the dead, and
do not let the bell count twice."

In Mafdet, we do not whisper it. We swear it at the Shrine, under
guardian-name, with witnesses. The bell rings once, and only once,
because someone is always counting.

